DOCUMENT();      

loadMacros(
   "PGstandard.pl",     # Standard macros for PG language
   "MathObjects.pl",
   #"source.pl",        # allows code to be displayed on certain sites.
   #"PGcourse.pl",      # Customization file for the course
    "Coalescent.pl",
);

# Print problem number and point value (weight) for the problem
TEXT(beginproblem());

# Show which answers are correct and which ones are incorrect
$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

##############################################################
#
#  Setup
#
#
Context("Numeric");

$population=random(1,20,1);
($An,$Bn, $E1, $E2)=&CalculateConstants($population); 
$an=Compute("$An");
$bn=Compute("$Bn");
$e1=Compute("$E1");
$e2=Compute("$E2");

#Answers
$answer="";
for ($i=1;$i<$population-1;$i++){
$answer.="\frac{1}{$i}+";
}
$answer.="\frac{1}{$population-1}";
##############################################################
#
#  Text
#
#

Context()->texStrings;
BEGIN_TEXT
Consider a population of $population gene, for which you have DNA sequences. If you want to estimate 
\(\theta\), the population mutation rate, you can use Waterson or Tajima \(\theta\)-estimators: $BR
This estimators are given by:$PAR
Tajima: $BR
\(\hat\pi=\frac{2}{n(n-1)}\sum_{i,j}\pi_{ij}\) , Waterson  \(  \hatθ_W=\frac{S_n}{a_n}\) 
where \(a_n =\sum_{i=1}^{n−1}\frac{1}{i}\) $PAR

Then, if \(\hat\pi\) and \(\hat\theta_W\) are compared, their difference is expected to be close to zero and deviations from zero are thus indicative that the basic coalescent model does not capture the variation in the data. Tajima (1989) normalised the difference in what is now known as Tajima’s D $PAR

\(D=\frac{\hat\pi-\hat\theta_W}{\sqrt{e_1S_n+e_2S_n(S_n-1)}}\) $BR
with $BR
\(e_1=\frac{n+1}{3a_n(n-1)}-\frac{1}{a_n^2}\) $BR
\(e_2=\frac{1}{a_n^2+b_n}(\frac{2(n^2+n+3)}{9n(n-1)}-\frac{n+2}{na_n}+\frac{b_n}{a_n^2})\) $BR
\(b_n=\sum_{i=1}^{n-1}\frac{1}{i^2}\) $PAR

Using your knowledge of sumatories, calculate the constants needed for the calculus of Waterson estimator and the D-Tajima test. $PAR 
\(a_n=\) \{$an->ans_rule\} $BR
\(b_n=\) \{$bn->ans_rule\} $BR
\(e_1=\) \{$e1->ans_rule\} $BR
\(e_2=\) \{$e2->ans_rule\}  $BR
END_TEXT
Context()->normalStrings;

##############################################################
#
#  Answers
#
#

ANS($an->with(tolerance=>.0001)->cmp);
ANS($bn->with(tolerance=>.0001)->cmp);
ANS($e1->with(tolerance=>.0001)->cmp);
ANS($e2->with(tolerance=>.0001)->cmp);

# relative tolerance --3.1412 is incorrect but 3.1413 is correct
# default tolerance is .01 or one percent.
Context()->texStrings;
SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$PAR SOLUTION $PAR
Using population size you have that n=$population $BR
Then, you only have to substitute n on the formulas below, for example $BR
 \(a_n =\sum_{i=1}^{n−1}\frac{1}{i}\) $BR
\(a_n=$answer\) $BR
So, by doing this, you will get: $BR
\(a_n=$an\)$BR
\(b_n=$bn\) $BR 
\(e_1=$e1\) $BR 
\(e_2=$e2\) $BR 

END_SOLUTION
Context()->normalStrings;
ENDDOCUMENT();        
